<font color="#FF0000">CHANGING THE RULES</font><br>
<tt>Wed Jul 23 16:57:26 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
Hi, my name is Nancy and I am one of the people who is working with POV to help facilitate this discussion.  A lot of people here have have said that the rules and messages that we learn about what's okay for girls and boys come from our families.  People have suggested that if parents made a commitment to raise their children diffrently, then we could start moving beyond these rules.<br><br>
What do you think it would look like if parents started encouraging boys to do things that girls have traditionally been taught to do and vice versa?  What I wonder about here is whether doing this still gives too much power to &quot;the rules&quot; because our decisions are being made in reaction to them.  What would it mean for people to make new rules altogether?<br>

<p><code>-- nrosenbaum@edc.org  (Nancy) </code><p>


